<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Which part of M1 typically increases the most during a banking panic?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Currency in circulation</option>
            <option letter="b">Demand deposits</option>
            <option letter="c">Traveler's checks</option>
            <option letter="d">Savings accounts</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>During banking panics, people often withdraw their deposits and hold currency instead, causing currency in circulation to increase while deposits decrease.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>On a bank's T-account, why are customer deposits listed as liabilities?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Because they belong to the government</option>
            <option letter="b">Because the bank owes this money to depositors</option>
            <option letter="c">Because they can't be used for loans</option>
            <option letter="d">Because they don't earn interest</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Deposits are liabilities because they represent money the bank owes to its depositors and must repay on demand.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How did the gold standard affect a country's ability to conduct monetary policy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It gave complete monetary freedom</option>
            <option letter="b">It restricted monetary policy options</option>
            <option letter="c">It had no effect on monetary policy</option>
            <option letter="d">It only affected foreign trade</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The gold standard restricted monetary policy because the money supply had to be maintained in proportion to the country's gold reserves.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What was the main advantage of the Bretton Woods system over the gold standard?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">More flexible but still stable</option>
            <option letter="b">Completely free exchange rates</option>
            <option letter="c">No need for reserves</option>
            <option letter="d">No international cooperation required</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Bretton Woods provided more flexibility than the rigid gold standard while maintaining stable exchange rates through a dollar-based system.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>When the Federal Reserve was created, what was its primary purpose?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">To regulate the stock market</option>
            <option letter="b">To provide an elastic currency</option>
            <option letter="c">To eliminate gold coins</option>
            <option letter="d">To fund government spending</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Fed was primarily created to provide an elastic currency that could expand or contract with the needs of the economy and prevent banking panics.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
